                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 (China) Eastern Publishing Co./30:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-30T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 30, 1937—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 30—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1248. Reference my despatch No. 956 of September 11, 1937, and previous
                    communications regarding “<hi rend="italic">Voice of China</hi>” published by
                    Eastern Publishing Company, owned by Max Granich. Settlement police report that
                    Mr. and Mrs. Max Granich left Shanghai on December 21, 1937, on the steamship
                        <hi rend="italic">Ranpura</hi> destined for Marseille, France.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
